re, water, air, and earth—and the phenomenology of creative imagination in Bachelard's Poetics of Space, his Poetics of Reverie, and in the fragments of Poetics of Fire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : History of Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Science. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846193940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438461939423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438461939/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles